  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "E7wiAXtWcMOs6GQgA51PxE/T9IU=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:41.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Argument\n\nPSS (Postal Service over Swarm) is a one-to-one messaging primitive where the sender mines a Trojan chunk whose address falls inside the recipient's neighborhood, then push-syncs it like any other chunk. The chunk payload is asymmetrically encrypted with the recipient's secp256k1 public key; third-party observers see only encrypted noise.\n\n## Key properties\n\n- **Direction:** one-to-one (sender \u2192 receiver)\n- **Encryption:** asymmetric (recipient's `beeNodePublicKey`)\n- **Max message:** ~4,060 bytes per chunk\n- **Latency:** 2\u201310 seconds (dominated by Trojan chunk mining + push-sync)\n- **Offline delivery:** yes \u2014 the Trojan chunk persists until its stamp TTL expires\n- **Receiver node:** **full node only** (light nodes cannot receive)\n- **Stamp type:** mutable or immutable\n\n## API\n\n```typescript\nawait bee.pssSend(batchId, topic, target, data, recipientPubKey)\nconst sub = bee.pssSubscribe(topic, { onMessage, onError, onClose })\n```\n\n## Why it matters\n\nPSS is the chat primitive for Connect's Swarm messaging layer: end-to-end encrypted, no servers, but slow enough (2\u201310s) that UX decisions like typing indicators stop making sense.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:41.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:41.000Z"
    }
  },
